    31тЖТ
    32тЖТ## Intro<a name="intro"></a>
    34тЖТTomli is a Python library for parsing [TOML](https://toml.io).
    35тЖТVersion 2.4.0 and later are compatible with [TOML v1.1.0](https://toml.io/en/v1.1.0).
    36тЖТOlder versions are [TOML v1.0.0](https://toml.io/en/v1.0.0) compatible.
    37тЖТ
    38тЖТA version of Tomli, the `tomllib` module,
    39тЖТwas added to the standard library in Python 3.11
    40тЖТvia [PEP 680](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0680/).
    41тЖТTomli continues to provide a backport on PyPI for Python versions
    42тЖТwhere the standard library module is not available
    43тЖТand that have not yet reached their end-of-life.
    44тЖТ
    45тЖТTomli uses [mypyc](https://github.com/mypyc/mypyc)
    46тЖТto generate binary wheels for most of the widely used platforms,
    47тЖТso Python 3.11+ users may prefer it over `tomllib` for improved performance.
    48тЖТPure Python wheels are available on any platform and should perform the same as `tomllib`.
    49тЖТ
    50тЖТ## Installation<a name="installation"></a>
    52тЖТ```bash
    53тЖТpip install tomli
    54тЖТ```
    55тЖТ
    56тЖТ## Usage<a name="usage"></a>
    58тЖТ### Parse a TOML string<a name="parse-a-toml-string"></a>
    60тЖТ```python
    61тЖТimport tomli
    62тЖТ
    63тЖТtoml_str = """
    64тЖТ[[players]]
    65тЖТname = "Lehtinen"
    66тЖТnumber = 26
    67тЖТ
    68тЖТ[[players]]
    69тЖТname = "Numminen"
    70тЖТnumber = 27
    71тЖТ"""
    72тЖТ
    73тЖТtoml_dict = tomli.loads(toml_str)
    74тЖТassert toml_dict == {
    75тЖТ    "players": [{"name": "Lehtinen", "number": 26}, {"name": "Numminen", "number": 27}]
    76тЖТ}
    77тЖТ```
    78тЖТ
    79тЖТ### Parse a TOML file<a name="parse-a-toml-file"></a>
    81тЖТ```python
    82тЖТimport tomli
    83тЖТ
    84тЖТwith open("path_to_file/conf.toml", "rb") as f:
    85тЖТ    toml_dict = tomli.load(f)
    86тЖТ```
    87тЖТ
    88тЖТThe file must be opened in binary mode (with the `"rb"` flag).
    89тЖТBinary mode will enforce decoding the file as UTF-8 with universal newlines disabled,
    90тЖТboth of which are required to correctly parse TOML.
    91тЖТ
    92тЖТ### Handle invalid TOML<a name="handle-invalid-toml"></a>
    94тЖТ```python
    95тЖТimport tomli
    96тЖТ
    97тЖТtry:
    98тЖТ    toml_dict = tomli.loads("]] this is invalid TOML [[")
    99тЖТexcept tomli.TOMLDecodeError:
   100тЖТ    print("Yep, definitely not valid.")
   101тЖТ```
   102тЖТ
   103тЖТNote that error messages are considered informational only.
   104тЖТThey should not be assumed to stay constant across Tomli versions.
   105тЖТ
   106тЖТ### Construct `decimal.Decimal`s from TOML floats<a name="construct-decimaldecimals-from-toml-floats"></a>
   108тЖТ```python
   109тЖТfrom decimal import Decimal
   110тЖТimport tomli
   111тЖТ
   112тЖТtoml_dict = tomli.loads("precision-matters = 0.982492", parse_float=Decimal)
   113тЖТassert isinstance(toml_dict["precision-matters"], Decimal)
   114тЖТassert toml_dict["precision-matters"] == Decimal("0.982492")
   115тЖТ```
   116тЖТ
   117тЖТNote that `decimal.Decimal` can be replaced with another callable that converts a TOML float from string to a Python type.
   118тЖТThe `decimal.Decimal` is, however, a practical choice for use cases where float inaccuracies can not be tolerated.
   119тЖТ
   120тЖТIllegal types are `dict` and `list`, and their subtypes.
   121тЖТA `ValueError` will be raised if `parse_float` produces illegal types.
   122тЖТ
   123тЖТ### Building a `tomli`/`tomllib` compatibility layer<a name="building-a-tomlitomllib-compatibility-layer"></a>
   125тЖТPython versions 3.11+ ship with a version of Tomli:
   126тЖТthe `tomllib` standard library module.
   127тЖТTo build code that uses the standard library if available,
   128тЖТbut still works seamlessly with Python 3.6+,
   129тЖТdo the following.
   130тЖТ
   131тЖТInstead of a hard Tomli dependency, use the following
   132тЖТ[dependency specifier](https://packaging.python.org/en/latest/specifications/dependency-specifiers/)
   133тЖТto only require Tomli when the standard library module is not available:
   134тЖТ
   135тЖТ```
   136тЖТtomli >= 1.1.0 ; python_version < "3.11"
   137тЖТ```
   138тЖТ
   139тЖТThen, in your code, import a TOML parser using the following fallback mechanism:
   140тЖТ
   141тЖТ```python
   142тЖТimport sys
   143тЖТ
   144тЖТif sys.version_info >= (3, 11):
   145тЖТ    import tomllib
   146тЖТelse:
   147тЖТ    import tomli as tomllib
   148тЖТ
   149тЖТtomllib.loads("['This parses fine with Python 3.6+']")
   150тЖТ```
   151тЖТ
   152тЖТ## FAQ<a name="faq"></a>
   154тЖТ### Why this parser?<a name="why-this-parser"></a>
   156тЖТ- it's lil'
   157тЖТ- pure Python with zero dependencies
   158тЖТ- the fastest pure Python parser [\*](#pure-python):
   159тЖТ  14x as fast as [tomlkit](https://pypi.org/project/tomlkit/),
   160тЖТ  2.1x as fast as [toml](https://pypi.org/project/toml/)
   161тЖТ- outputs [basic data types](#how-do-toml-types-map-into-python-types) only
   162тЖТ- 100% spec compliant: passes all tests in
   163тЖТ  [toml-lang/toml-test](https://github.com/toml-lang/toml-test)
   164тЖТ  test suite
   165тЖТ- thoroughly tested: 100% branch coverage
   166тЖТ
   167тЖТ### Is comment preserving round-trip parsing supported?<a name="is-comment-preserving-round-trip-parsing-supported"></a>
   169тЖТNo.
   170тЖТ
   171тЖТThe `tomli.loads` function returns a plain `dict` that is populated with builtin types and types from the standard library only.
   172тЖТPreserving comments requires a custom type to be returned so will not be supported,
   173тЖТat least not by the `tomli.loads` and `tomli.load` functions.
   174тЖТ
   175тЖТLook into [TOML Kit](https://github.com/sdispater/tomlkit) if preservation of style is what you need.
   176тЖТ
   177тЖТ### Is there a `dumps`, `write` or `encode` function?<a name="is-there-a-dumps-write-or-encode-function"></a>
   179тЖТ[Tomli-W](https://github.com/hukkin/tomli-w) is the write-only counterpart of Tomli, providing `dump` and `dumps` functions.
   180тЖТ
   181тЖТThe core library does not include write capability, as most TOML use cases are read-only, and Tomli intends to be minimal.
   182тЖТ
   183тЖТ### How do TOML types map into Python types?<a name="how-do-toml-types-map-into-python-types"></a>
   185тЖТ| TOML type        | Python type         | Details                                                      |
   186тЖТ| ---------------- | ------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
   187тЖТ| Document Root    | `dict`              |                                                              |
   188тЖТ| Key              | `str`               |                                                              |
   189тЖТ| String           | `str`               |                                                              |
   190тЖТ| Integer          | `int`               |                                                              |
   191тЖТ| Float            | `float`             |                                                              |
   192тЖТ| Boolean          | `bool`              |                                                              |
   193тЖТ| Offset Date-Time | `datetime.datetime` | `tzinfo` attribute set to an instance of `datetime.timezone` |
   194тЖТ| Local Date-Time  | `datetime.datetime` | `tzinfo` attribute set to `None`                             |
   195тЖТ| Local Date       | `datetime.date`     |                                                              |
   196тЖТ| Local Time       | `datetime.time`     |                                                              |
   197тЖТ| Array            | `list`              |                                                              |
   198тЖТ| Table            | `dict`              |                                                              |
   199тЖТ| Inline Table     | `dict`              |                                                              |
   200тЖТ
   201тЖТ## Performance<a name="performance"></a>
   203тЖТThe `benchmark/` folder in this repository contains a performance benchmark for comparing the various Python TOML parsers.
   204тЖТ
   205тЖТBelow are the results for commit [064e492](https://github.com/hukkin/tomli/tree/064e492919b2338def788753b8c981c9131334c0).
   206тЖТ
   207тЖТ### Mypyc generated wheel<a name="mypyc-generated-wheel"></a>
   209тЖТ```console
   210тЖТfoo@bar:~/dev/tomli$ python --version
   211тЖТPython 3.14.2
   212тЖТfoo@bar:~/dev/tomli$ pip freeze
   213тЖТpytomlpp==1.1.0
   214тЖТrtoml==0.13.0
   215тЖТtoml==0.10.2
   216тЖТtomli @ file:///home/foo/dev/tomli
   217тЖТtomlkit==0.13.3
   218тЖТfoo@bar:~/dev/tomli$ python benchmark/run.py
   219тЖТParsing data.toml 5000 times:
   220тЖТ------------------------------------------------------
   221тЖТ    parser |  exec time | performance (more is better)
   222тЖТ-----------+------------+-----------------------------
   223тЖТ     rtoml |    0.328 s | baseline (100%)
   224тЖТ  pytomlpp |    0.365 s | 89.75%
   225тЖТ     tomli |    0.838 s | 39.12%
   226тЖТ      toml |     3.01 s | 10.90%
   227тЖТ   tomlkit |     20.7 s | 1.59%
   228тЖТ```
   229тЖТ
   230тЖТ### Pure Python<a name="pure-python"></a>
   232тЖТ```console
   233тЖТfoo@bar:~/dev/tomli$ python benchmark/run.py
   234тЖТParsing data.toml 5000 times:
   235тЖТ------------------------------------------------------
   236тЖТ    parser |  exec time | performance (more is better)
   237тЖТ-----------+------------+-----------------------------
   238тЖТ     rtoml |    0.323 s | baseline (100%)
   239тЖТ  pytomlpp |    0.365 s | 88.40%
   240тЖТ     tomli |     1.44 s | 22.36%
   241тЖТ      toml |     3.03 s | 10.65%
   242тЖТ   tomlkit |     20.6 s | 1.57%
   243тЖТ```
